## <summary>SELinux policy module for the Dungeon Master service.</summary>
##
## Phase 7 hardening (spec §13). Targets AlmaLinux 10's SELinux targeted
## policy. The trusted-LAN deployment posture means the service runs
## under ``unconfined_service_t`` (the default for systemd-managed
## services without a specific transition), which already has wide
## access. This module is intentionally minimal: it exists as a
## reviewable, version-controlled hook so that *if* the deployment
## posture ever tightens, the policy module is the place to land
## domain transitions, dontaudit rules, and bespoke allow blocks.
##
## What this module DOES today:
## - Declares the ``policy_module`` namespace ``dungeon_master`` so the
##   companion ``dungeon-master.fc`` file-context entries land under a
##   reviewable identifier in ``semodule -l`` output.
## - Pulls in the ``require`` block for the types referenced by the .fc
##   file so checkmodule can resolve them. (.fc entries that name
##   contexts like ``var_lib_t`` need the kernel to know the type
##   exists at module load time — the require makes that explicit.)
## - Carries no custom allow rules. The targeted policy's
##   ``unconfined_service_t`` already covers everything the service
##   needs against ``var_lib_t`` / ``var_log_t`` / ``http_port_t``.
##
## What this module DOES NOT do (operationally handled by
## ``deploy/selinux/install.sh``):
## - Port labelling for 8001 (``semanage port -a -t http_port_t``).
## - Boolean for nginx → localhost (``setsebool -P httpd_can_network_connect 1``).
## - ``restorecon`` over the data and log paths.
## These are operator-time actions, not module declarations; mixing them
## here would require generating boolean / port DDL that's better kept
## in a shell script.
##
## When to extend:
## - If audit2allow surfaces denials under enforcing mode (the install
##   path runs the service under its default domain; AVC denials get
##   logged to /var/log/audit/audit.log). Inspect, decide whether to
##   accept (allow rule), suppress (dontaudit), or fix the root cause.
## - If the project later confines the service into its own domain
##   (e.g. ``dungeon_master_t``), this is where ``type_transition``
##   from ``init_t`` lands.
## - If file contexts diverge from ``var_lib_t`` / ``var_log_t``
##   (e.g. introducing ``dungeon_master_data_t`` for tighter scoping),
##   declare the new type here AND update ``dungeon-master.fc``.
##
## Build (manual):
##   checkmodule -m -M -o dungeon-master.mod dungeon-master.te
##   semodule_package -o dungeon-master.pp \
##       -m dungeon-master.mod -f dungeon-master.fc
##   semodule -i dungeon-master.pp

module dungeon-master 1.0.0;

require {
    type var_lib_t;
    type var_log_t;
    type http_port_t;
}

# No allow rules at this revision — the service runs as
# unconfined_service_t and the stock AL10 targeted policy already
# permits the operations the app needs. The require block above
# exists so checkmodule resolves the referenced types when packaging
# the .fc entries alongside.
